<DOC><DOCNO> AP901001-0227 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-10-01-90 1255EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a BC-APIndustryNews 7thAdd   10-01 5502</FIRST><SECOND>BC-AP Industry News, 7th Add,0614</SECOND><BYLINE>PERSONNEL</BYLINE><HEAD>Trounson First Civil Top Editor for Stars and Stripes</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   W. Robert Trounson, deputy business editor of theLos Angeles Times, was named the first civilian chief editor ofPacific Stars and Stripes on Sept. 26.   Trounson worked for the Times for 23 years. In 1974-75, hestudied Japanese history, politics, language and art at StanfordUniversity under a journalism fellowship.   He was a copy editor and news editor at the Stars and Stripes in1963-67.   Stripes ombudsman Philip M. Foisie recommended naming of acivilian chief editor last January after studying allegations ofcensorship at the paper, including charges by staff members thatsenior editors had killed stories critical of the military or ofhost countries.   The editor in chief's position was previously held by thepaper's senior military officer, who now holds the title ofcommander-publisher, with editorial control delegated to thecivilian chief editor.</TEXT><HEAD>Lake Appointed Publisher in Marion, Ohioi</HEAD><DATELINE>MARION, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Steven C. Lake, publisher of The Free Press,a semiweekly in Canton, was appointed publisher and general managerof The Marion Star.   The appointment was effective Sept. 24.   Before The Free Press, Lake was advertising director of TheRepository in Canton for seven years. He also worked for VermontPublishing Co.</TEXT><HEAD>General Manager of Phoenix Newspapers Resigns</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: Wm. is cq</NOTE><DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Phoenix Newspapers Inc. said Sept. 25 thatvice president and general manager Wm. R. Hogan will resign tobecome president of a land management company he has formed with apartner.   The company said in a statement that Hogan would step down Dec.31 to work full time with Natural Resources Group Inc. and becomean officer in Oakridge Holdings Inc., a funeral services and realestate company.</TEXT><BYLINE>DEATHS</BYLINE><BYLINE>Thomas Fichter</BYLINE><DATELINE>RESTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Thomas C. Fichter, senior vice president andchief financial officer of the American Newspaper PublishersAssociation, died Sept. 29. He was 51.   The cause of death was not disclosed.   Fichter, who had been with the organization for 29 years, alsowas treasurer of the ANPA Foundation and chairman and president ofANPA's Credit Bureau Inc.</TEXT><BYLINE>Harold King</BYLINE><DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Harold King, a reporter who covered the battle ofStalingrad and forged close ties with French leader Charles deGaulle, died Sept. 24 of heart failure. He was 91.   King worked as a correspondent in Paris for The Wall StreetJournal and the Financial Times and later headed Reuters' Parisbureau from 1944 to 1967.   Reuters also sent King to the Soviet Union, where he wrote onthe Red Army victory at Stalingrad and covered Stalin's breakup ofthe Communist International in 1943.   He cultivated his contacts with de Gaulle during the general'spostwar withdrawal from political life.   After leaving Reuters' Paris bureau, King worked as acorrespondent for the Toronto Telegram.</TEXT><BYLINE>Rev. Lazlo Ladany</BYLINE><DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Rev. Lazlo Ladany, whose journal ofChina-watching made him famous on university campuses and inembassies on both sides of the Iron Curtain, died Sept. 23 of lungcancer. He was 76.   The revolution of 1949 forced the Hungarian-born Ladany andother Jesuits to flee China. He arrived in the British colony ofHong Kong and began publishing China News Analysis in 1953, theworld's oldest China-watching journal. Operating out of a smallroom in a student hostel at the University of Hong Kong, Ladanymonitored news broadcasts from almost every Chinese province.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE><TEXT/><